Package: HausdorffGoF
Type: Package
Version: 0.3.0
Title: P-Values of the One- and Two-Sample Hausdorff
    Goodness-of-Fit Test
Authors@R: c(
    person("Dimitrina S.", "Dimitrova",
           email = "D.Dimitrova@citystgeorges.ac.uk", role = c("aut")),
    person("Yun", "Jia",
           email = "yunjia2019@gmail.com",   role = c("aut", "cre")),
    person("Vladimir K.", "Kaishev",
           email = "Vladimir.Kaishev.1@citystgeorges.ac.uk", role = c("aut")))
Description: Computes the test statistic and p-values of the one-sample and
    two-sample Hausdorff (H) goodness-of-fit tests proposed by Dimitrova, Jia,
    and Kaishev (2026a, 2026b). The H statistic measures the Hausdorff distance
    between the planar curves of two cumulative distribution functions (cdfs)
    under the Chebyshev (l-infinity) metric, equalling the side length of the
    largest axis-aligned square inscribable between the two curves; in the
    univariate case this coincides with the Levy metric. Three settings are
    covered: (i) one-sample, comparing a sample to a prespecified continuous
    null cdf; (ii) two-sample univariate; and (iii) two-sample bivariate.
    Exact one-sample p-values are evaluated in O(n^2 log n) time via the
    'Exact-KS-FFT' method of Dimitrova, Kaishev, and Tan (2020)
    <doi:10.18637/jss.v095.i10>; two-sample p-values are obtained by exact
    or Monte Carlo permutation. A key advantage of the H test is that its
    sensitivity can be directed towards the left tail, body, or right tail
    of the distribution by tuning a scale parameter sigma, making it
    significantly outperform classical alternatives such as Kolmogorov-Smirnov,
    Cramer-von Mises, and Anderson-Darling, especially in the tails, while
    achieving power comparable to the Wasserstein test. This makes the H test
    particularly appealing in finance, economics, astronomy, and extreme value
    theory. Optimal scale selection (sigma*) is integrated directly into the
    unified interface Hausdorff_test() via the scale_psi argument, and the S3
    generics Hausdorff_test() and Hausdorff_stat() dispatch automatically to
    the appropriate routine based on input type, with null distributions
    specified via the distribution() constructor.
